Recommended built in locators in Playwright are:

Reference link :
http://playwright.dev/python/docs/locators

1. page.get_by_role()
               it finds elements on webpage by their role
               button, link, textbox, heading, checkbox, radio, etc

2. page.get_by_lable()
               it finds elements on webpage by their label
               for example, if there is a text box with label "username",

3. page.get_by_placeholder()
               it finds elements on webpage by their placeholder text
               for example, if there is a text box with placeholder "enter your name",

4. page.get_by_alt_text()
                it finds elements on webpage by their alt text
                for example, if there is an image with alt text "company logo",

5. page.get_by_title()
                it finds elements on webpage by their title attribute
                for example, if there is an element with title "submit button",

6. page.get_by_test_id()
                it finds elements on webpage by their data-testid attribute
                for example, if there is an element with data-testid "login-button",

  ******************************************************************************************
Xpath and CSS selectors are also supported in Playwright,
but the above locators are recommended for better readability and maintainability of test scripts.

- Sample HTML code for reference:

<div class = card, id = "card1">


  Xpath Locator:

  // -> search everywhere in the document ( DOM )
   => take drone and look everywhere


  / -> search from the root element
    => go floor by floor and search for the element

  tag names:
 div -> search for div element
 span -> search for span element
 input -> search for input element

 attribute:
    id -> search for element with specific id
    class -> search for element with specific class
    name -> search for element with specific name
    type -> search for element with specific type
    value -> search for element with specific value
    text() -> search for element with specific text content

   xpath syntax:
    //div[@id = "card1"]
    // div [@class= "card"]
    // div [@id = "card1" and @class = "card"]

    xpath in playwright:
    page.locator('//div[@id = "card1"]')
    page.locator('//div[@class= "card"]')
    page.locator('//div[@id = "card1" and @class = "card"]')

CSS Selector:

  tag name:
    div -> search for div element
    span -> search for span element
    input -> search for input element

  attribute:
    id -> search for element with specific id
    class -> search for element with specific class
    name -> search for element with specific name
    type -> search for element with specific type
    value -> search for element with specific value
    text() -> search for element with specific text content

  css selector syntax:
   #card1 -> search for element with id "card1"
   .card -> search for element with class "card"
   div#card1 -> search for div element with id "card1"
   div.card -> search for div element with class "card"

css selector in playwright:
   page.locator('#card1')
   page.locator('.card')
   page.locator('div#card1')
   page.locator('div.card')

   contains in xpath
    //div[contains(@class, "card")]

contains in xpath
-> checks if it includes the value in the attribute




